The '''olive-green tanager''' ('''''Orthogonys chloricterus''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Mitrospingidae]]. It is [[endemic]] to [[Brazil]].{{refn|name=IOC12.1|{{Cite web |date=2022-02-01 |editor-last=Gill |editor-first=F. |editor2-last=Donsker |editor2-first=D. |editor3-last=Rasmussen |editor3-first=P. |title=IOC World Bird List (v 12.1) |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/warblers/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220530053456/https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/warblers/ |archive-date=2022-05-30 |access-date=2022-05-30}}}}

==Taxonomy and systematics==
The olive-green tanager and the three other species in family Mitrospingidae were previously placed in family [[Thraupidae]], the "true" tanagers. A 2013 publication detailed how they did not belong there and proposed the new family for them.{{refn|{{Cite journal |last1=Barker |first1=F. Keith |last2=Burns |first2=Kevin J. |last3=Klicka |first3=John |last4=Lanyon |first4=Scott M. |last5=Lovette |first5=Irby J. |date=2012-12-29 |title=Going to extremes: contrasting rates of diversification in a recent radiation of New World passerine birds |url=https://academic.oup.com/sysbio/article/62/2/298/1671243 |journal=[[Systematic Biology]] |language=en-US |volume=62 |issue=2 |pages=298–320 |doi=10.1093/sysbio/sys094 |jstor=23485140 |pmid=23229025 |access-date=2022-05-30|doi-access=free }}}} The North and South American Classification Committees of the [[American Ornithological Society]] accepted the new placement in July 2017 and March 2019, respectively.{{refn|name=58Supp|{{Cite journal |last1=Chesser |first1=R. Terry |last2=Burns |first2=Kevin J. |last3=Cicero |first3=Carla |last4=Dunn |first4=Jon L. |last5=Kratter |first5=Andrew W. |last6=Lovette |first6=Irby J. |last7=Rasmussen |first7=Pamela C. |last8=Remsen |first8=J. V. Jr. |last9=Rising |first9=James D. |last10=Stotz |first10=Douglas F. |last11=Winker |first11=Kevin |date=2017-07-05 |title=Fifty-eighth supplement to the American Ornithological Society's ''Check-list of North American Birds'' |journal=[[Ornithology (journal)|The Auk]] |language=en-US |volume=134 |issue=3 |pages=751–773 |doi=10.1642/AUK-17-72.1 |s2cid=91015792 |doi-access=free }}}}{{refn|name=SACClist|{{Cite web |last1=Remsen |first1=J. V. Jr. |last2=Areta |first2=Juan Ignacio |last3=Bonaccorso |first3=Elisa |last4=Claramunt |first4=Santiago |last5=Jaramillo |first5=Alvaro |last6=Lane |first6=Daniel F. |last7=Pacheco |first7=José Fernando |last8=Robbins |first8=Mark B. |last9=Stiles |first9=F. Gary |date=2022-01-31 |title=A classification of the bird species of South America |url=https://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCBaseline.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220518162855/https://www.museum.lsu.edu/~Remsen/SACCBaseline.htm |archive-date=2022-05-18  |access-date=2022-05-30 |website=[[Louisiana State University]] |publisher=[[American Ornithological Society]] |language=en-US |first10=Kevin J. |last10=Zimmer }}}} The [[International Ornithological Committee]] (IOC) followed suit in January 2018.{{r|IOC12.1}}

The olive-green tanager is the only member of its genus and has no subspecies.{{r|IOC12.1}}

==Description==
The olive-green tanager is {{convert|18|to|19|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. The adult is olive green above and dull yellow below; it has a tinge of olive on the sides and flanks.{{refn|name=OGTA-BOW|{{Cite journal |last1=Hilty |first1=Steven |last2=Juana |first2=Eduardo de |date=2020-03-04 |editor-last=Hoyo |editor-first=J. del |editor2-last=Elliott |editor2-first=A. |editor3-last=Sargatal |editor3-first=J. |editor4-last=Christie |editor4-first=D. A. |editor5-last=Juana |editor5-first=E. de |title=Olive-green Tanager (''Orthogonys chloricterus''), version 1.0. |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/olgtan1/1.0/introduction |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220530063009/https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/olgtan1/1.0/introduction |archive-date=2022-05-30 |access-date=2022-05-30 |website=Birds of the World |publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]] |location=Ithaca, New York |language=en-US |doi=10.2173/bow.olgtan1.01|s2cid=216225042 }}}}

==Distribution and habitat==
The olive-green tanager is found only in southeastern Brazil, from [[Espírito Santo]] state south to eastern [[Santa Catarina (state)|Santa Catarina]] and northeastern [[Rio Grande do Sul]]. It inhabits the interior and edges of humid [[montane forest]] at elevations of {{convert|900|to|1800|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{r|OGTA-BOW}}

==Behavior==
===Feeding===
The olive-green tanager's diet is primarily insects, though it also eats fruit. It typically forages in flocks of its own species that may number up to 20 individuals but more usually have about eight. It feeds in the mid- to upper levels of the forest, usually picking prey from leaves, and it also sallies for flying insects.{{r|OGTA-BOW}}

===Breeding===
One olive-green tanager was noted carrying nest material to a [[bromeliad]] in a large tree. No other information has been published about its breeding [[phenology]].{{r|OGTA-BOW}}

===Vocalization===
The olive-green tanager's song has been rendered as "tséé-si, si, si, tséé-si, si, si."{{refn|{{Cite web |last=Gagliardi |first=Ricardo |title=XC471138 · Olive-green Tanager · ''Orthogonys chloricterus'' |url=https://www.xeno-canto.org/471138 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220530065101/https://xeno-canto.org/471138 |archive-date=2022-05-30  |access-date=2022-05-30 |website=xeno-canto |language=en-US }}}} Its call is a buzzy "tseee" {{refn|{{Cite web |last=Fischer |first=Jerome |title=XC340702 · Olive-green Tanager · ''Orthogonys chloricterus'' |url=https://www.xeno-canto.org/340702 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220530065058/https://xeno-canto.org/340702 |archive-date=2022-05-30  |access-date=2022-05-30 |website=xeno-canto |language=en-US }}}} and it also calls "wheek!" while foraging.{{r|OGTA-BOW}}{{refn|{{Cite web |last=Boesman |first=Peter |title=XC227019 · Olive-green Tanager · ''Orthogonys chloricterus'' |url=https://www.xeno-canto.org/227019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220530065054/https://xeno-canto.org/227019 |archive-date=2022-05-30  |access-date=2022-05-30 |website=xeno-canto |language=en-US }}}}

==Status==
The [[IUCN]] has assessed the olive-green tanager as being of Least Concern.{{r|IUCN}} "Despite local population declines and fragmentation, its long-term viability should be assured if protection continues for the parks and reserves where it remains."{{r|OGTA-BOW}}

